this carries over even into english. so, don't be surprised if you hear expressions such as "yes-la" or "i'm not sure-la". it just implies respect. reach. in bhutan, the verb 'reach' means to 'take' or 'accompany' (a person). for example: "i'll reach you to the bus station" means "i'll take/accompany you to the bus station." cousin-brother, cousin-sister. extended families living under one roof are common in bhutan. as a result, the dividing line between siblings and cousins is blurred, and so it is not uncommon to be introduced to a "cousin-brother" or "cousin-sister". although these people are just cousins, the 